\section{Conclusion}
\vspace{-2mm}
In this paper, we strived to show that large-scale channel information plays the key role on predictive resource allocation for delay tolerant services. Toward this goal, we formulated a time slot scheduling and power allocation problem minimizing the total energy consumed for conveying a given number of bits before a long deadline, where the large and small-scale channel gains are perfectly known for all time slots. We showed that only the water-filling level and threshold in the optimal solution contains future information, which can be estimated accurately with large-scale channel gains when the small-scale channels in each frame are ergodic.
Simulation results validated our analysis and showed that the estimation errors of the large-scale channel gains have little impact on energy saving.

